</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:year>2012</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Productivity, wages, and marriage : the case of major league baseball</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:id>9257FACE-9CE8-402A-BC64-861683ECF646</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Married players earn more than single players holding all else equal but they are no more productive at their jobs. Explanations are explored.</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:year>2012</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Our results show that marriage has an impact on productivity for lower ability men, though this result is sensitive to the empirical specification and weakly significant. In addition, despite the lack of any effect on productivity, high ability married players earn roughly 16 - 20 percent more than their single counterparts. We discuss possible reasons why employers may favor married men. These involve greater sportsmanship, team leadership and reliability. In other results we find that teams with a greater proportion of married players are more likely to win.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Our work has already received significant attention in non academic environments. In particular, we have been interviewed by the BBC, Wall Street Journal and Forbes magazine, in addition to numerous other media outlets. 

